      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/output-comparison-rh-index",
      "rationale": "Simulated relative hemolysis index (RH) compared against experimental measurements from the FDA generic centrifugal pump benchmark dataset at all 5 operating points. Agreement within 15% at each point; RH < 1 criterion satisfied for all worst-case conditions. Validation metric: normalized root-mean-square error NRMSE = 0.09 across the operating envelope."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/qoi-relevance-hemolysis",
      "rationale": "The primary QoI is the normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) and relative hemolysis index (RH). These quantities are directly linked to the clinical endpoint of red blood cell damage under CPB conditions. The QoI is computed from scalar stress integration along particle pathlines, which is the standard approach for CFD hemolysis prediction per ASTM F1841. Relevance to COU is confirmed: worst-case operating point identification requires sensitivity of NIH to flow-speed combinations, which the model directly provides."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
